# Cursor Entrypoint & Read Order

- Start from `docs/START_HERE.md` for the shared task-routing index and weak-tool/manual fallback path.
- Use this file for Cursor-specific read order on top of that shared entrypoint.
- Read `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`, then `docs/rules/architecture-protocol.md`.
- For transaction or outbound work, also read `docs/rules/transactions.md` and `docs/rules/resilience.md`.
- For audit logging, centralized monitoring, or API-edge traceability work, also read `docs/rules/audit-log.md`.
- For incident hotfixes, malicious-parameter blocking, temporary blocked paths, or API-edge request screening, also read `docs/rules/request-screening.md` and prefer native ASP.NET Core middleware / filters. Keep the feature behind focused extension methods, and treat missing `RequestScreening:Enabled` config as disabled.
- For endpoint protection, build/test slowness, CI exclusions, Apex One constraints, Phase C firewall hardening, or exception-leak prevention, also read `docs/rules/endpoint-protection.md` early and prioritize `ExceptionLeakTests` before broader firewall expansion.
- For external APIs, SDKs, shared services, or legacy integrations, also load `external-integration-discovery.mdc`.
- Treat `docs/`, `templates/`, and `skeleton/` as the source of truth. Do not invent parallel conventions.
- This repository is the Blueprint layer in the recommended Blueprint / Seed / Target workflow.
- For project setup, namespace conversion, or directory renaming on a Seed folder, read `docs/starter-pack/project-setup-protocol.md` before other workflow rules.
- If a target repo provides `docs/specs/`, follow that feature spec before applying default blueprint assumptions.
- Treat raw requirement files such as `docs/requirements/raw/` as source material; convert them into `docs/specs/` before implementation when possible.
- Use Seed / Sandbox to prototype clean reference implementations when the target repo is noisy, legacy-heavy, or stylistically inconsistent.
- When integrating into a Target repo, preserve Target naming, style, and boundaries; do not copy blueprint-specific abstractions verbatim unless the target explicitly adopts them.
- For legacy project modifications, load `legacy-project-rule.mdc` and do not mix `TransactionScope` into `IDbTransaction`-based paths; also re-check async/await consistency to avoid sync-over-async deadlocks.
- For Seed -> Target translation into an existing repo, load `seed-to-legacy-target-translation.mdc`.
- For Seed -> Target translation into a greenfield or early-stage repo, load `seed-to-new-project-target-translation.mdc`.
- If the request or audit matches, also load `refactor-uow.mdc`, `add-resilience.mdc`, `external-integration-discovery.mdc`, `api-standard.mdc`, or `legacy-project-rule.mdc`.
- If `docs/specs/` contains a feature spec, it overrides default guidance.
